Space Complexity-
The space complexity of an algorithm is the total space taken by the algorithm with respect
to the input size.
Space complexity means taken auxilary space and input space in the memory.
Auxilary space means the extra space used to solve the problem.
Input size is used to store the input.

Example -

x = 2, y = 5,  z = 7
total = (x+y+z)
print(total)

So input space is x,y,z
and auxilary space is total variable.


Constraint - 
Constraint errors usually mean your data type is too small to hold large numbers,
or you exceeded memory limits.

How to Fix TLE and Constraint ErrorsMatch Complexity to Constraints: 
Use problem constraints to choose the right algorithm.

A safe rule is that your code should perform under 10⁸ operations per second.
N ≤ 10: O(N!) or \(O(2^N)\) is acceptable.
N ≤ 10³: O(N²) is acceptable.
N ≤ 10⁵: \(O(N \log N)\) or O(N) is required.
N ≤ 10⁹: \(O(\log N)\) or O(1) is required.
Use Fast I/O: Slow reading and printing can trigger TLE.
In C++:
Add ios_base::sync_with_stdio(false);
cin.tie(NULL); at the start of your code.
In Java:
Switch from Scanner to BufferedReader and StringTokenizer.
Avoid Primitive Overflow: If values exceed ≈ 2 × 10⁹, use long long in C++ or long in Java instead of int to prevent constraint/overflow errors.
Remove Nested Loops:
Replace O(N²) brute-force solutions with efficient patterns like two-pointer, sliding window, or hash maps to achieve O(N) or \(O(N \log N)\) time.
If you share the problem constraints (e.g., N ≤ 10⁵), the problem statement, and your current code, I can help you refactor it to avoid these errors.









